# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: microscale-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] In contrast to the relatively early flowering of organotransition-metal chemistry (1955 to the present), the corresponding development of actinide organometallic chemistry has taken place largely within the past 15 or so years.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] During this period, 5f organometallic science has blossomed, and it is now apparent that the actinides have a rich, intricate, and highly informative organometallic chemistry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Intriguing parallels to and sharp differences from the d-block elements have emerged.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Actinides can coordinate the organic active groups or bind to carbon by the covalent bonds.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The necessity of obtaining accurate thermodynamic quantities for the actinide elements and their compounds was recognized at the outset of the Manhattan Project, when a dedicated team of scientists and engineers initiated the program to exploit nuclear energy for military purposes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Since the end of World War II, both fundamental and applied objectives have motivated a great deal of further study of actinide thermodynamics.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The possibility of using unique properties of lanthanides in the nanotechnology is demonstrated.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The origination of linear and nonlinear optical properties of lanthanide compounds with phthalocyanines, porphyrins, naphthalocyanines, and their analogs in solutions and condensed state and the prospects of obtaining novel materials on their basis are discussed.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Based on the electronic structure and properties of lanthanides and their compounds, namely, optical and magnetic characteristics, electronic and ionic conductivity, and fluctuating valence, molecular engines are classified.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] It is shown that thermodynamically stable nanoparticles of Ln*x*M*y* composition can be formed by d elements of the second halves of the series, i.e., those arranged after M = Mn, Tc, and Re.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Generally, ingested insoluble actinide compounds such as high-fired uranium dioxide and mixed oxide (MOX) fuel will pass through the digestive system with little effect since they cannot dissolve and be absorbed by the body.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Inhaled actinide compounds, however, will be more damaging as they remain in the lungs and irradiate the lung tissue.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Ingested Low-fired oxides and soluble salts such as nitrate can be absorbed into the blood stream.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] If they are inhaled then it is possible for the solid to dissolve and leave the lungs.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Hence the dose to the lungs will be lower for the soluble form.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Radon and radium are not actinides—they are both radioactive daughters from the decay of uranium.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Aspects of their biology and environmental behaviour is discussed at radium in the environment.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] In India, a large amount of thorium ore can be found in the form of monazite in placer deposits of the Western and Eastern coastal dune sands, particularly in the Tamil Nadu coastal areas.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The residents of this area are exposed to a naturally occurring radiation dose ten times higher than the worldwide average.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Thorium has been linked to liver cancer.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] In the past thoria (thorium dioxide) was used as a contrast agent for medical X-ray radiography but its use has been discontinued.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Uranium is about as abundant as arsenic or molybdenum.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Significant concentrations of uranium occur in some substances such as phosphate rock deposits, and minerals such as lignite, and monazite sands in uranium-rich ores (it is recovered commercially from these sources).
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Seawater contains about 3.3 parts per billion of uranium by weight as uranium(VI) forms soluble carbonate complexes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The extraction of uranium from seawater has been considered as a means of obtaining the element.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Because of the very low specific activity of uranium the chemical effects of it upon living things can often outweigh the effects of its radioactivity.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Plutonium, like other actinides, readily forms a plutonium dioxide (*plutonyl*) core (PuO2).
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] In the environment, this plutonyl core readily complexes with carbonate as well as other oxygen moieties (OH−, NO− 2, NO− 3, and SO2− 4) to form charged complexes which can be readily mobile with low affinities to soil.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Some early evidence for nuclear fission was the formation of a short-lived radioisotope of barium which was isolated from neutron irradiated uranium (139Ba, with a half-life of 83 minutes and 140Ba, with a half-life of 12.8 days, are major fission products of uranium).
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] At the time, it was thought that this was a new radium isotope, as it was then standard radiochemical practice to use a barium sulfate carrier precipitate to assist in the isolation of radium.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The PUREX process is a liquid–liquid extraction ion-exchange method used to reprocess spent nuclear fuel, in order to extract primarily uranium and plutonium, independent of each other, from the other constituents.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The current method of choice is to use the PUREX liquid–liquid extraction process which uses a tributyl phosphate/hydrocarbon mixture to extract both uranium and plutonium from nitric acid.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] This extraction is of the nitrate salts and is classed as being of a solvation mechanism.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] For example, the extraction of plutonium by an extraction agent (S) in a nitrate medium occurs by the following reaction.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] A complex bond is formed between the metal cation, the nitrates and the tributyl phosphate, and a model compound of a dioxouranium(VI) complex with two nitrates and two triethyl phosphates has been characterised by X-ray crystallography.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] After the dissolution step it is normal to remove the fine insoluble solids, because otherwise they will disturb the solvent extraction process by altering the liquid-liquid interface.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] It is known that the presence of a fine solid can stabilize an emulsion.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Emulsions are often referred to as third phases in the solvent extraction community.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] An organic solvent composed of 30% tributyl phosphate (TBP) in a hydrocarbon solvent, such as kerosene, is used to extract the uranium as UO2(NO3)2·2TBP complexes, and plutonium as similar complexes, from other fission products, which remain in the aqueous phase.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The transuranium elements americium and curium also remain in the aqueous phase.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The nature of the organic soluble uranium complex has been the subject of some research.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] A series of complexes of uranium with nitrate and trialkyl phosphates and phosphine oxides have been characterized.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Plutonium is separated from uranium by treating the kerosene solution with aqueous ferrous sulphamate, which selectively reduces the plutonium to the +3 oxidation state.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The plutonium passes into the aqueous phase.
[src:microscale-chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The uranium is stripped from the kerosene solution by back-extraction into nitric acid at a concentration of ca.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] This aspect of agricultural chemistry deals with the role of molecular chemistry in agriculture as well as the negative consequences.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Plant biochemistry encompasses the chemical reactions that occur within plants.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] In principle, knowledge at a molecular level informs technologies for providing food.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Particular focus is on the biochemical differences between plants and other organisms as well as the differences within the plant kingdom, such as dicotyledons vs monocotyledons, gymnosperms vs angiosperms, C2- vs C4-fixers, etc.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Chemical materials developed to assist in the production of food, feed, and fiber include herbicides, insecticides, fungicides, and other pesticides.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Pesticides are chemicals that play an important role in increasing crop yield and mitigating crop losses.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] These work to keep insects and other animals away from crops to allow them to grow undisturbed, effectively regulating pests and diseases.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Disadvantages of pesticides include contamination of the ground and water (see persistent organic pollutants).
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] They may be toxic to non-target species, including birds, fish, pollinators, as well as the farmworkers themselves.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Agricultural chemistry often aims at preserving or increasing the fertility of soil with the goals of maintaining or improving the agricultural yield and improving the quality of the crop.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Soils are analyzed with attention to the inorganic matter (minerals), which comprise most of the mass of dry soil, and organic matter, which consists of living organisms, their degradation products, humic acids and fulvic acids.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] While organic fertilizers are time-honored, their use has largely been displaced by chemicals produced from mining (phosphate rock) and the Haber-Bosch process.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] The use of these materials dramatically increased the rate at which crops are produced, which is able to support the growing human population.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Common fertilizers include urea, ammonium sulphate, diammonium phosphate, and calcium ammonium phosphate.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Agricultural chemistry encompasses the science and technology of producing not only edible crops, but feedstocks for fuels ("biofuels") and materials.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Ethanol fuel obtained by fermentation of sugars.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Biodiesel is derived from fats, both animal- and plant-derived.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Methane can be recovered from manure and other ag wastes by microbial action.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Lignocellulose is a promising precursor to new materials.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Biocatalysis is used to produce a number of food products.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] More than five billion tons of high fructose corn syrup are produced annually by the action of the immobilized enzyme glucose isomerase of corn-derived glucose.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Emerging technologies are numerous, including enzymes for clarifying or debittering of fruit juices.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] A variety of potentially useful chemicals are obtained by engineered plants.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Bioremediation is a green route to biodegradation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Genetically Modified Organisms (GMO's) are plants or living things that have been altered at a genomic level by scientists to improve the organisms characteristics.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] These characteristics include providing new vaccines for humans, increasing nutrients supplies, and creating unique plastics.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] They may also be able to grow in climates that are typically not suitable for the original organism to grow in.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Examples of GMO's include virus resistant tobacco and squash, delayed ripening tomatoes, and herbicide resistant soybeans.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] GMO's came with an increased interest in using biotechnology to produce fertilizer and pesticides.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Due to an increased market interest in biotechnology in the 1970s, there was more technology and infrastructure developed, a decreased cost, and an advance in research.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Since the early 1980s, genetically-modified crops have been incorporated.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Increased biotechnological work calls for the union of biology and chemistry to produce improved crops, a main reason behind this being the increasing amount of food needed to feed a growing population.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] That being said, concerns with GMO's include potential antibiotic resistance from eating a GMO.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] There are also concerns about the long term effects on the human body since many GMO's were recently developed.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] In the United States, all foods containing GMO's must be labeled as such.
[src:microscale-chemistry/agricultural-chemistry] Particularly relevant is proteomics as protein (nutrition) guides much of agriculture.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Alchemists attempted to purify, mature, and perfect certain materials.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Common aims were chrysopoeia, the transmutation of "base metals" (e.g., lead) into "noble metals" (particularly gold); the creation of an elixir of immortality; and the creation of panaceas able to cure any disease.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The perfection of the human body and soul was thought to result from the alchemical *magnum opus* ("Great Work").
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The concept of creating the philosopher's stone was variously connected with all of these projects.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Islamic and European alchemists developed a basic set of laboratory techniques, theories, and terms, some of which are still in use today.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] They did not abandon the Ancient Greek philosophical idea that everything is composed of four elements, and they tended to guard their work in secrecy, often making use of cyphers and cryptic symbolism.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] In Europe, the 12th-century translations of medieval Islamic works on science and the rediscovery of Aristotelian philosophy gave birth to a flourishing tradition of Latin alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] This late medieval tradition of alchemy would go on to play a significant role in the development of early modern science (particularly chemistry and medicine).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Modern discussions of alchemy are generally split into an examination of its exoteric practical applications and its esoteric spiritual aspects, despite criticisms by scholars such as Eric J.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Holmyard and Marie-Louise von Franz that they should be understood as complementary.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The former is pursued by historians of the physical sciences, who examine the subject in terms of early chemistry, medicine, and charlatanism, and the philosophical and religious contexts in which these events occurred.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The latter interests historians of esotericism, psychologists, and some philosophers and spiritualists.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The subject has also made an ongoing impact on literature and the arts.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The word alchemy comes from Old French *alkimie*, used in Medieval Latin as *alchymia*.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] This name was itself adopted from the Arabic word *al-kīmiyā* (الكيمياء).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The Arabic *al-kīmiyā* in turn was a borrowing of the Late Greek term *khēmeía* (χημεία), also spelled *khumeia* (χυμεία) and *khēmía* (χημία), with *al-* being the Arabic definite article 'the'.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Together this association can be interpreted as 'the process of transmutation by which to fuse or reunite with the divine or original form'.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Several etymologies have been proposed for the Greek term.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The first was proposed by Zosimos of Panopolis (3rd–4th centuries), who derived it from the name of a book, the *Khemeu*.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Hermann Diels argued in 1914 that it rather derived from χύμα, used to describe metallic objects formed by casting.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] Others trace its roots to the Egyptian name *kēme*, meaning 'black earth', which refers to the fertile and auriferous soil of the Nile valley, as opposed to red desert sand.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] According to the Egyptologist Wallis Budge, the Arabic word **al-kīmiya*ʾ* actually means "the Egyptian [science]", borrowing from the Coptic word for "Egypt", **kēme** (or its equivalent in the Mediaeval Bohairic dialect of Coptic, **khēme**).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] This Coptic word derives from Demotic **kmỉ**, itself from ancient Egyptian **kmt**.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p01] The ancient Egyptian word referred to both the country and the colour "black" (Egypt was the "black Land", by contrast with the "red Land", the surrounding desert).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alchemy comprises a plurality of philosophical traditions extending across approximately four millennia and spanning three continents.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The marked tendency of these traditions toward esoteric and highly symbolic modes of expression renders it difficult to reconstruct their patterns of mutual influence and genealogical relationships.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Chinese alchemy was closely connected to Taoism and Indian alchemy with the Dharmic faiths.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In contrast, Western alchemy developed its philosophical system mostly independent of but influenced by various Western religions.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] It is still an open question whether these three strands share a common origin, or to what extent they influenced each other.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The start of Western alchemy may generally be traced to Hellenistic Egypt, where the city of Alexandria was a center of alchemical knowledge, and retained its pre-eminence through most of the Greek and Roman periods.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Following the work of André-Jean Festugière, modern scholars see alchemical practice in the Roman Empire as originating from the Egyptian goldsmith's art, Greek philosophy and different religious traditions.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Tracing the origins of the alchemical art in Egypt is complicated by the pseudepigraphic nature of texts from the Greek alchemical corpus.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The treatises of Zosimos of Panopolis, the earliest historically attested author (fl. c.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] 300), can help in situating the other authors.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Zosimus based his work on that of older alchemical authors, such as Mary the Jewess, Pseudo-Democritus, and Agathodaimon, but very little is known about any of these authors.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The most complete of their works, the *Four Books* of Pseudo-Democritus, were probably written in the first century AD.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Recent scholarship tends to emphasize the testimony of Zosimus, who traced the alchemical arts back to Egyptian metallurgical and ceremonial practices.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] It has also been argued that early alchemical writers borrowed the vocabulary of Greek philosophical schools but did not implement any of its doctrines in a systematic way.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Zosimos of Panopolis wrote in the *Final Abstinence* (a.k.a. the *Final Count*) that the ancient practice of "tinctures" (the technical Greek term for the alchemical arts) had been taken over by certain "demons" who taught the art only to those who offered them sacrifices.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Since Zosimos also called the demons "the guardians of places" (οἱ κατὰ τόπον ἔφοροι, *hoi katà tópon éphoroi*) and those who offered them sacrifices "priests" (ἱερέα, *hieréa*), it is fairly clear that he was referring to the gods of Egypt and their priests.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] While critical of the kind of alchemy he associated with the Egyptian priests and their followers, Zosimos nonetheless saw the tradition's recent past as rooted in the rites of the Egyptian temples.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Zosimos of Panopolis asserted that alchemy dated back to Pharaonic Egypt where it was the domain of the priestly class, though there is little to no evidence for his assertion.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alchemical writers used classical figures from Greek (e.g., Hades), Roman (e.g., Lucius), and Egyptian mythology to illuminate their works and allegorize alchemical transmutation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These included the pantheon of gods related to the classical planets, Isis, Osiris, Jason, and many others.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The central figure in the mythology of alchemy is Hermes Trismegistus (Ἑρμῆς ὁ Τρισμέγιστος, 'Hermes the Thrice-Greatest').
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His name is derived from the god Thoth and his Greek counterpart, Hermes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Hermes and his caduceus or serpent-staff, were among alchemy's principal symbols.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] According to Clement of Alexandria, he wrote what were called the "forty-two books of Hermes", covering all fields of knowledge.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The *Hermetica* are a compendium of texts attributed to Hermes Trismegistus.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Many of them have close historical connections with Western alchemical philosophy and practice (which was sometimes called the Hermetic philosophy by its practitioners).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By modern convention, the *Hermetica* is usually subdivided into two main categories: the "technical" and "religio-philosophical" *Hermetica*.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The "technical" *Hermetica* deals with alchemy, astrology, medicine, pharmacology, and magic.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Its oldest parts were written in Greek and may go back as far as the second or third century BC.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Many of the texts in the "technical" *Hermetica* were later translated, first into Arabic and then into Latin, often being extensively revised and expanded throughout the centuries.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Some of them were also originally written in Arabic.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In other cases their status as an original work or translation remains unclear.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These Arabic and Latin Hermetic texts were widely copied throughout the Middle Ages.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The most famous of these texts is the *Emerald Tablet*, also known as the *Smaragdine Table* or the *Tabula Smaragdina*, a compact and cryptic text.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The earliest known versions of it are four Arabic recensions preserved in mystical and alchemical treatises between the 8th and 10th centuries AD—chiefly the *Secret of Creation* (سر الخليقة, *Sirr al-Khalīqa*) and the *Secret of Secrets* (سرّ الأسرار, *Sirr al-Asrār*).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Medieval commentators such as Ortolanus interpreted it as a "foundational text" of alchemical instructions for producing the philosopher's stone and making gold.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The dawn of Western alchemy is sometimes associated with that of metallurgy, extending back to 3500 BC.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Many writings were lost when the Roman emperor Diocletian ordered the burning of alchemical books after suppressing a revolt in Alexandria (AD 292).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Few original Egyptian documents on alchemy have survived, most notable among them the Stockholm papyrus and the Leyden papyrus X.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Dating from AD 250 to 300, they contained recipes for dyeing and making artificial gemstones, cleaning and fabricating pearls, and manufacturing of imitation gold and silver.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These writings lack the mystical, philosophical elements of alchemy, but do contain the works of Bolus of Mendes (or Pseudo-Democritus), which aligned these recipes with theoretical knowledge of astrology and the classical elements.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Between the time of Bolus and Zosimos, the change took place that transformed this metallurgy into a Hermetic art.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alexandria acted as a melting pot for philosophies of Pythagoreanism, Platonism, Stoicism, and Gnosticism that formed the origin of alchemy's character.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] An important example of alchemy's roots in Greek philosophy, originated by Empedocles and developed by Aristotle, was that all things in the universe were formed from only four elements: earth, air, water, and fire.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] According to Aristotle, each element had a sphere to which it belonged and to which it would return if left undisturbed.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Later alchemists extensively developed the mystical aspects of this concept.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alchemy coexisted alongside emerging Christianity.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Lactantius believed Hermes Trismegistus had prophesied its birth.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Augustine of Hippo later affirmed this in the 4th and 5th centuries, but also condemned Trismegistus for idolatry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Examples of pagan, Christian, and Jewish alchemists can be found during this period.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Most of the Greco-Roman alchemists preceding Zosimos are known only by pseudonyms, such as Moses of Alexandria, Isis, Cleopatra the Alchemist, Pseudo-Democritus, and Ostanes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Other authors such as Komarios and Chymes are known only through surviving fragments of text.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] After AD 400, Greek alchemical writers occupied themselves solely in commenting on the works of these predecessors.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By the middle of the 7th century, alchemy was almost an entirely mystical discipline.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] It was at that time that Khalid Ibn Yazid sparked its migration from Alexandria to the Islamic world, facilitating the translation and preservation of Greek alchemical texts in the 8th and 9th centuries.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Greek alchemy was preserved in medieval Byzantine manuscripts after the fall of Roman Egypt, yet historians have only relatively recently begun to study and development of Greek alchemy in the Byzantine period.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The 2nd millennium BC Vedas describe a connection between eternal life and gold.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Buddhist texts from the 2nd to 5th centuries mention the transmutation of base metals to gold.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] According to some scholars Greek alchemy may have influenced Indian alchemy but there are no hard evidences to back this claim.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The goals of alchemy in India included the creation of a divine body (*divya-deham*) and immortality while still embodied (*jīvan-mukti*).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Sanskrit alchemical texts include much material on the manipulation of mercury and sulphur, that are homologized with the semen of the god Śiva and the menstrual blood of the goddess Devī.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Some early alchemical writings seem to have their origins in the Kaula tantric schools associated to the teachings of the personality of Matsyendranath.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Other early writings are found in the Jaina medical treatise *Kalyāṇakārakam* of Ugrāditya, written in South India in the early 9th century.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Two famous early Indian alchemical authors were Nāgārjuna Siddha and Nityanātha Siddha.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His book *Rasendramangalam* is an example of Indian alchemy and medicine.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Nityanātha Siddha wrote *Rasaratnākara*, which was also a highly influential work.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In Sanskrit, *rasa* translates to "mercury", and Nāgārjuna Siddha was said to have developed a method of converting mercury into gold.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] An example of academic scholarship on Indian alchemy is *The Alchemical Body* by Indologist David Gordon White.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] A modern bibliography on Indian alchemical studies has been written by White.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The contents of 39 Sanskrit alchemical treatises have been analysed in detail in Gerrit Jan Meulenbeld's *History of Indian Medical Literature* (*HIML*).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The discussion of these works in the *HIML* gives a summary of the contents of each work, their special features, and where possible the evidence concerning their dating.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Chapter 13 of the *HIML*, *Various works on rasaśāstra and ratnaśāstra* ('Various works on alchemy and gems') gives brief details of another 655 treatises.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In some cases, Meulenbeld gives notes on the contents and authorship of these works; in other cases references are made only to the unpublished manuscripts of these titles.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] A great deal remains to be discovered about Indian alchemical literature.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] After the fall of the Roman Empire, the focus of alchemical development moved to the Islamic World.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Much more is known about Islamic alchemy because it was better documented: indeed, most of the earlier writings that have come down through the years were preserved as Arabic translations.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The word *alchemy* itself was derived from the Arabic word *al-kīmiyā* (الكيمياء).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The early Islamic world was a melting pot for alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Platonic and Aristotelian thought, which had already been somewhat appropriated into Hermetic science, continued to be assimilated during the late 7th and early 8th centuries through Syriac translations and scholarship.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the late ninth and early tenth centuries, the Arabic works attributed to Jābir ibn Hayyān (Latinized as "Geber" or "Geberus") introduced a new approach to alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Islamic philosophers also made great contributions to alchemical Hermeticism.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The most influential author in this regard was arguably ibn Hayyan. ibn Hayyan's ultimate goal was *takwin*, the artificial creation of life in the alchemical laboratory—up to and including human life.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He analysed each Aristotelian element in terms of four basic qualities of *hotness*, *coldness*, *dryness*, and *moistness*.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] According to ibn Hayyan, in each metal two of these qualities were interior and two were exterior.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] For example, lead was externally cold and dry, while gold was hot and moist.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Thus, ibn Hayyan theorized, by rearranging the qualities of one metal, a different metal would result.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By this reasoning, the search for the philosopher's stone was introduced to Western alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Ibn Hayyan developed an elaborate numerology whereby the root letters of a substance's name in Arabic, when treated with various transformations, held correspondences to the element's physical properties.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The atomic theory of corpuscularianism, where all physical bodies possess an inner and outer layer of minute particles or corpuscles, also has its origins in the work of ibn Hayyan.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] From the 9th to 14th centuries, alchemical theories faced criticism from a variety of practical Muslim chemists, including Al-Kindi, Abū al-Rayhān al-Bīrūnī, Avicenna and Ibn Khaldun.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In particular, they wrote refutations against the idea of the transmutation of metals.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] From the 14th century onwards, many materials and practices originally belonging to Indian alchemy (*Rasayana*) were assimilated in the Persian texts written by Muslim scholars.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Researchers have found evidence that Chinese alchemists and philosophers discovered complex mathematical phenomena that were shared with Arab alchemists during the medieval period.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Discovered first in China before the Common Era, the "magic square of three" was propagated to followers of Jabir ibn Hayyan at some point over the proceeding several hundred years.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Other commonalities shared between the two alchemical schools of thought include discrete naming for ingredients and heavy influence from the natural elements.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The Silk Road provided a clear path for the exchange of goods, ideas, ingredients, religion, and many other aspects of life with which alchemy is intertwined.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Whereas European alchemy eventually centered on the transmutation of base metals into noble metals, Chinese alchemy had a more obvious connection to medicine.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The philosopher's stone of European alchemists can be compared to the elixir of life sought by Chinese alchemists.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the Hermetic view, these two goals were not unconnected, and the philosopher's stone was often equated with the universal panacea; therefore, the two traditions may have had more in common than initially appears.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] As early as 317 AD, Ge Hong documented the use of metals, minerals, and elixirs in early Chinese medicine.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Hong identified three ancient Chinese documents—titled the *Scripture of Great Clarity*, the *Scripture of the Nine Elixirs*, and the *Scripture of the Golden Liquor*—as texts containing fundamental alchemical information.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He also described alchemy, along with meditation, as the sole spiritual practices that could allow one to gain immortality or to transcend to a higher state of being.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In his work *Inner Chapters of the Book of the Master Who Embraces Spontaneous Nature* (317 AD), Hong argued that alchemical solutions such as elixirs were preferable to traditional medicinal treatment due to the spiritual protection they could provide.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the centuries following Ge Hong's death, the emphasis placed on alchemy as a spiritual practice among Chinese Taoists was reduced.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In 499 AD, Tao Hongjing refuted Hong's statement that alchemy is as important a spiritual practice as Shangqing meditation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] While Hongjing did not deny the power of alchemical elixirs to grant immortality or provide divine protection, he ultimately found the *Scripture of the Nine Elixirs* to be ambiguous and spiritually unfulfilling, aiming to implement more accessible practising techniques.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the early 700s, *Neidan* (a.k.a. internal alchemy) was adopted by Daoists as a new form of alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] *Neidan* emphasized appeasing the inner gods that inhabit the human body by practising alchemy with compounds naturally found in the body, rather than the mixing of natural resources that was so emphasized in early Dao alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] For example, saliva was often considered nourishment for the inner gods and did not require any conscious alchemical reaction to produce.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The inner gods were not thought of as physical presences occupying each person, but rather a collection of deities that are each said to represent and protect a specific body part or region.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although those who practised *Neidan* prioritized meditation over external alchemical strategies, many of the same elixirs and constituents from previous Daoist alchemical schools of thought continued to be utilized in tandem with meditation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Eternal life remained a consideration for *Neidan* alchemists, as it was believed that one would become immortal if an inner god were to be immortalized within them through spiritual fulfilment.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Chinese alchemy was closely connected to Taoist techniques in traditional Chinese medicine like acupuncture and moxibustion.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the early Song dynasty, followers of this Taoist idea—chiefly the elite and upper class—would ingest mercuric sulfide, which, though tolerable in low levels, led many to suicide.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The introduction of alchemy to Latin Europe may be dated to 11 February 1144, with the completion of Robert of Chester's translation of the *Liber de compositione alchemiae* (Book on the Composition of Alchemy) from an Arabic work attributed to Khalid ibn Yazid.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although European craftsmen and technicians pre-existed, Robert notes in his preface that alchemy (here still referring to the elixir rather than to the art itself) was unknown in Latin Europe at the time of his writing.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The translation of Arabic texts concerning numerous disciplines including alchemy flourished in 12th-century Toledo, Spain, through contributors like Gerard of Cremona and Adelard of Bath.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Translations of the time included the Turba Philosophorum, and the works of Avicenna and Muhammad ibn Zakariya al-Razi.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These brought with them many new words to the European vocabulary for which there was no previous Latin equivalent.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alcohol, carboy, elixir, and athanor are examples.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Meanwhile, theologian contemporaries of the translators made strides towards the reconciliation of faith and experimental rationalism, thereby priming Europe for the influx of alchemical thought.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The 11th-century theologian Anselm of Canterbury put forth the opinion that faith and rationalism were compatible and encouraged rationalism in a Christian context.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the early 12th century, Peter Abelard followed Anselm's work, laying down the foundation for acceptance of Aristotelian thought before the first works of Aristotle had reached the West.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the early 13th century, Robert Grosseteste used Abelard's methods of analysis and added the use of observation, experimentation, and conclusions when conducting scientific investigations.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Grosseteste also did much work to reconcile Platonic and Aristotelian thinking.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Through much of the 12th and 13th centuries, alchemical knowledge in Europe remained centered on translations, and new Latin contributions were not made.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The efforts of the translators were succeeded by that of the encyclopaedists.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the 13th century, Albertus Magnus and Roger Bacon were the most notable of these, their work summarizing and explaining the newly imported alchemical knowledge in Aristotelian terms.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Albertus Magnus, a Dominican friar, is known to have written works such as the *Book of Minerals* where he observed and commented on the operations and theories of alchemical authorities like Hermes Trismegistus, pseudo-Democritus, and unnamed alchemists of his time.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Albertus critically compared these to the writings of Aristotle and Avicenna, where they concerned the transmutation of metals.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] From the time shortly after his death through to the 15th century, more than 28 alchemical tracts were misattributed to him, a common practice giving rise to his reputation as an accomplished alchemist.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Likewise, alchemical texts have been attributed to Albert's student Thomas Aquinas.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Bacon's writings integrated morality, salvation, alchemy, and the prolongation of life.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His correspondence with Clement highlighted this, noting the importance of alchemy to the papacy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Like the Greeks before him, Bacon acknowledged the division of alchemy into practical and theoretical spheres.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He noted that the theoretical lay outside the scope of Aristotle, the natural philosophers, and all Latin writers of his time.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The practical confirmed the theoretical, and Bacon advocated its uses in natural science and medicine.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In later European legend, he became an archmage.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In particular, along with Albertus Magnus, he was credited with the forging of a brazen head capable of answering its owner's questions.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Soon after Bacon, the influential work of Pseudo-Geber (sometimes identified as Paul of Taranto) appeared.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His *Summa Perfectionis* remained a staple summary of alchemical practice and theory through the medieval and renaissance periods.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] It was notable for its inclusion of practical chemical operations alongside sulphur-mercury theory, and the unusual clarity with which they were described.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By the end of the 13th century, alchemy had developed into a fairly structured system of belief.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Adepts believed in the macrocosm-microcosm theories of Hermes; namely, that processes that affect minerals and other substances could have an effect on the human body (for example, if one could learn the secret of purifying gold, one could use the technique to purify the human soul).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] They believed in the four elements and the four qualities as described above, and they had a strong tradition of cloaking their written ideas in a labyrinth of coded jargon set with traps to mislead the uninitiated.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Finally, the alchemists practised their art: they actively experimented with chemicals and made observations and theories about how the universe operated.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Their entire philosophy revolved around their belief that the human soul was divided within itself after the fall of Adam.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By purifying the two parts of humankind's soul, humans could be reunited with God.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the 14th century, alchemy became more accessible to Europeans outside the confines of Latin-speaking churchmen and scholars.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alchemical discourse shifted from scholarly philosophical debate to an exposed social commentary on the alchemists themselves.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Dante Alighieri, Piers Plowman, and Geoffrey Chaucer all painted unflattering pictures of alchemists as thieves and liars.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Pope John XXII's 1317 edict *Spondent quas non-exhibent* forbade the false promises of transmutation made by pseudo-alchemists.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Roman Catholic Inquisitor General Nicholas Eymerich's *Directorium Inquisitorum*, written in 1376, associated alchemy with the performance of demonic rituals, which Eymerich differentiated from magic performed in accordance with Christian scripture.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This did not, however, lead to any change in the Inquisition's monitoring or prosecution of alchemists.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In 1404, Henry IV of England banned the practice of multiplying metals by the passing of the Gold and Silver Act 1403 (5 Hen.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] 4) (although it was possible to buy a licence to attempt to make gold alchemically, and a number were granted by Henry VI and Edward IV).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These critiques and regulations centered more around pseudo-alchemical charlatanism than the actual study of alchemy, which continued with an increasingly Christian tone.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The 14th century saw the Christian imagery of death and resurrection employed in the alchemical texts of Petrus Bonus, John of Rupescissa, and in works written in the name of Raymond Lull and Arnold of Villanova.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Nicolas Flamel is a well-known alchemist to the point where he had many pseudepigraphic imitators.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although the historical Flamel existed, the writings and legends assigned to him only appeared in 1612.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] A common idea in European alchemy in the medieval era was a metaphysical "Homeric chain of wise men that link[ed] heaven and earth" that included ancient pagan philosophers and other important historical figures.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] , meaning "redness", was adopted by alchemists and signalled alchemical success, and the end of the great work.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] During the Renaissance, Hermetic and Platonic foundations were restored to European alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The dawn of medical, pharmaceutical, occult, and entrepreneurial branches of alchemy followed.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the late 15th century, Marsilio Ficino translated the Corpus Hermeticum and the works of Plato into Latin.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These were previously unavailable to Europeans who for the first time had a full picture of the alchemical theory that Bacon had declared absent.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Renaissance Humanism and Renaissance Neoplatonism guided alchemists away from physics to refocus on mankind as the alchemical vessel.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Esoteric systems developed that blended alchemy into a broader occult Hermeticism, fusing it with magic, astrology, and Christian Kabbalah.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] A key figure in this development was Heinrich Cornelius Agrippa (1486–1535), a German who received his Hermetic education in Italy in the schools of the humanists.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In his *De Occulta Philosophia*, he attempted to merge Judaism's Kabbalah, Hermeticism, and alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He was instrumental in spreading this new blend of Hermeticism outside the borders of Italy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Paracelsus, born Philippus Aureolus Theophrastus Bombastus von Hohenheim (1493–1541), cast alchemy into a new form, rejecting some of Agrippa's occultism and moving away from chrysopoeia.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Paracelsus pioneered the use of chemicals and minerals in medicine and wrote, "Many have said of Alchemy, that it is for the making of gold and silver.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His Hermetical views were that sickness and health in the body relied on the harmony of humankind as the microcosm and Nature the macrocosm.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He took an approach different from those before him, using this analogy not in the manner of soul-purification but in the manner that humans must have certain balances of minerals in their bodies, and that certain illnesses of the body had chemical remedies that could cure them.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Iatrochemistry refers to the pharmaceutical applications of alchemy championed by Paracelsus.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] John Dee (13 July 1527 – December 1608) followed Agrippa's occult tradition.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although better known for angel summoning, divination, and his role as astrologer, cryptographer, and consultant to Elizabeth I of England, Dee's alchemical *Monas Hieroglyphica*, written in 1564 was his most popular and influential work.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] His writing portrayed alchemy as a sort of terrestrial astronomy in line with the Hermetic axiom *as above, so below*.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] During the 17th century, a short-lived "supernatural" interpretation of alchemy became popular, including support by fellows of the Royal Society: Robert Boyle and Elias Ashmole.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Proponents of the supernatural interpretation of alchemy believed that the philosopher's stone might be used to summon and communicate with angels.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Entrepreneurial opportunities were common for the alchemists of Renaissance Europe.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Alchemists were contracted by the elite for practical purposes related to mining, medical services, and the production of chemicals, medicines, metals, and gemstones.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor, in the late 16th century, famously received and sponsored various alchemists at his court in Prague, including Dee and his associate Edward Kelley.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] King James IV of Scotland, Julius, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg, Henry V, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg, Augustus, Elector of Saxony, Julius Echter von Mespelbrunn, and Maurice, Landgrave of Hesse-Kassel all contracted alchemists.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] John's son Arthur Dee worked as a court physician to Michael I of Russia and Charles I of England but also compiled the alchemical book *Fasciculus Chemicus*.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although most of these appointments were legitimate, the trend of pseudo-alchemical fraud continued through the Renaissance.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] *Betrüger* would use sleight of hand, or claims of secret knowledge to make money or secure patronage.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Legitimate mystical and medical alchemists such as Michael Maier and Heinrich Khunrath wrote about fraudulent transmutations, distinguishing themselves from the con artists.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] False alchemists were sometimes prosecuted for fraud.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The terms "chemia" and "alchemia" were used as synonyms in the early modern period, and the differences between alchemy, chemistry and small-scale assaying and metallurgy were not as neat as in the present day.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] There were important overlaps between practitioners, and trying to classify them into alchemists, chemists and craftsmen is anachronistic.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] For example, Tycho Brahe (1546–1601), an alchemist better known for his astronomical and astrological investigations, had a laboratory built at his Uraniborg observatory/research institute.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Michael Sendivogius (*Michał Sędziwój*, 1566–1636), a Polish alchemist, philosopher, medical doctor and pioneer of chemistry wrote mystical works but is also credited with distilling oxygen in a lab sometime around 1600.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Sendivogious taught his technique to Cornelius Drebbel who, in 1621, applied this in a submarine.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Isaac Newton devoted considerably more of his writing to the study of alchemy (see Isaac Newton's occult studies) than he did to either optics or physics.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Other early modern alchemists who were eminent in their other studies include Robert Boyle, and Jan Baptist van Helmont.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Their Hermeticism complemented rather than precluded their practical achievements in medicine and science.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The decline of European alchemy was brought about by the rise of modern science with its emphasis on rigorous quantitative experimentation and its disdain for "ancient wisdom".
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although the seeds of these events were planted as early as the 17th century, alchemy still flourished for some two hundred years, and in fact may have reached its peak in the 18th century.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] As late as 1781 James Price claimed to have produced a powder that could transmute mercury into silver or gold.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Robert Boyle (1627–1691) pioneered the scientific method in chemical investigations.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] He assumed nothing in his experiments and compiled every piece of relevant data.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Boyle would note the place in which the experiment was carried out, the wind characteristics, the position of the Sun and Moon, and the barometer reading, all just in case they proved to be relevant.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This approach eventually led to the founding of modern chemistry in the 18th and 19th centuries, based on revolutionary discoveries and ideas of Lavoisier and John Dalton.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Beginning around 1720, a rigid distinction began to be drawn for the first time between "alchemy" and "chemistry".
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] By the 1740s, "alchemy" was now restricted to the realm of gold making, leading to the popular belief that alchemists were charlatans, and the tradition itself nothing more than a fraud.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In order to protect the developing science of modern chemistry from the negative censure to which alchemy was being subjected, academic writers during the 18th-century scientific Enlightenment attempted to divorce and separate the "new" chemistry from the "old" practices of alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This move was mostly successful, and the consequences of this continued into the 19th, 20th and 21st centuries.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] During the occult revival of the early 19th century, alchemy received new attention as an occult science.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The esoteric or occultist school that arose during the 19th century held the view that the substances and operations mentioned in alchemical literature are to be interpreted in a spiritual sense, less than as a practical tradition or protoscience.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This interpretation claimed that the obscure language of the alchemical texts, which 19th century practitioners were not always able to decipher, were an allegorical guise for spiritual, moral or mystical processes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Two seminal figures during this period were Mary Anne Atwood and Ethan Allen Hitchcock, who independently published similar works regarding spiritual alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Both rebuffed the growing successes of chemistry, developing a completely esoteric view of alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Atwood wrote: "No modern art or chemistry, notwithstanding all its surreptitious claims, has any thing in common with Alchemy." Atwood's work influenced subsequent authors of the occult revival including Eliphas Levi, Arthur Edward Waite, and Rudolf Steiner.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Hitchcock, in his *Remarks Upon Alchymists* (1855) attempted to make a case for his spiritual interpretation with his claim that the alchemists wrote about a spiritual discipline under a materialistic guise in order to avoid accusations of blasphemy from the church and state.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In 1845, Baron Carl Reichenbach, published his studies on Odic force, a concept with some similarities to alchemy, but his research did not enter the mainstream of scientific discussion.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In 1946, Louis Cattiaux published the Message Retrouvé, a work that was at once philosophical, mystical and highly influenced by alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In his lineage, many researchers, including Emmanuel and Charles d'Hooghvorst, are updating alchemical studies in France and Belgium.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Several women appear in the earliest history of alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Michael Maier names four women who were able to make the philosophers' stone: Mary the Jewess, Cleopatra the Alchemist, Medera, and Taphnutia.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Zosimos's sister Theosebia (later known as Euthica the Arab) and Isis the Prophetess also played roles in early alchemical texts.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The first alchemist whose name we know was Mary the Jewess (c.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Early sources claim that Mary (or Maria) devised a number of improvements to alchemical equipment and tools as well as novel techniques in chemistry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Her best known advances were in heating and distillation processes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The laboratory water-bath, known eponymously (especially in France) as the bain-marie, is said to have been invented or at least improved by her.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Essentially a double-boiler, it was (and is) used in chemistry for processes that required gentle heating.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The tribikos (a modified distillation apparatus) and the kerotakis (a more intricate apparatus used especially for sublimations) are two other advancements in the process of distillation that are credited to her.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Although we have no writing from Mary herself, she is known from the early-fourth-century writings of Zosimos of Panopolis.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] After the Greco-Roman period, women's names appear less frequently in alchemical literature.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Towards the end of the Middle Ages and beginning of the Renaissance, due to the emergence of print, women were able to access the alchemical knowledge from texts of the preceding centuries.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Caterina Sforza, the Countess of Forlì and Lady of Imola, is one of the few confirmed female alchemists after Mary the Jewess.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] As she owned an apothecary, she would practice science and conduct experiments in her botanic gardens and laboratories.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Being knowledgeable in alchemy and pharmacology, she recorded all of her alchemical ventures in a manuscript named *Experimenti* ('Experiments').
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The manuscript contained more than four hundred recipes covering alchemy as well as cosmetics and medicine.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] One of these recipes was for the water of talc.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Talc, which makes up talcum powder, is a mineral which, when combined with water and distilled, was said to produce a solution which yielded many benefits.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] These supposed benefits included turning silver to gold and rejuvenation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] When combined with white wine, its powder form could be ingested to counteract poison.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Furthermore, if that powder was mixed and drunk with white wine, it was said to be a source of protection from any poison, sickness, or plague.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Other recipes were for making hair dyes, lotions, lip colours.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] There was also information on how to treat a variety of ailments from fevers and coughs to epilepsy and cancer.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In addition, there were instructions on producing the quintessence (or aether), an elixir which was believed to be able to heal all sicknesses, defend against diseases, and perpetuate youthfulness.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] She also wrote about creating the illustrious philosophers' stone.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Some women known for their interest in alchemy were Catherine de' Medici, the Queen of France, and Marie de' Medici, the following Queen of France, who carried out experiments in her personal laboratory.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Also, Isabella d'Este, the Marchioness of Mantua, made perfumes herself to serve as gifts.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Due to the proliferation in alchemical literature of pseudepigrapha and anonymous works, however, it is difficult to know which of the alchemists were actually women.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This contributed to a broader pattern in which male authors credited prominent noblewomen for beauty products with the purpose of appealing to a female audience.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] For example, in *Ricettario galante* ("Gallant Recipe-Book"), the distillation of lemons and roses was attributed to Elisabetta Gonzaga, the duchess of Urbino.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the same book, Isabella d'Aragona, the daughter of Alfonso II of Naples, is accredited for recipes involving alum and mercury.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Ippolita Maria Sforza is even referred to in an anonymous manuscript about a hand lotion created with rose powder and crushed bones.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] As the sixteenth century went on, scientific culture flourished and people began collecting "secrets".
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] During this period "secrets" referred to experiments, and the most coveted ones were not those which were bizarre, but the ones which had been proven to yield the desired outcome.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In this period, the only book of secrets ascribed to a woman was *I secreti della signora Isabella Cortese* ('The Secrets of Signora Isabella Cortese').
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] This book contained information on how to turn base metals into gold, medicine, and cosmetics.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] However, it is rumoured that a man, Girolamo Ruscelli, was the real author and only used a female voice to attract female readers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] In the nineteenth-century, Mary Anne Atwood's *A Suggestive Inquiry into the Hermetic Mystery* (1850) marked the return of women during the occult revival.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The history of alchemy has become a recognized subject of academic study.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] A large collection of books on alchemy is kept in the Bibliotheca Philosophica Hermetica in Amsterdam.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Journals which publish regularly on the topic of Alchemy include *Ambix*, published by the Society for the History of Alchemy and Chemistry, and *Isis*, published by the History of Science Society.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Western alchemical theory corresponds to the worldview of late antiquity in which it was born.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Concepts were imported from Neoplatonism and earlier Greek cosmology.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] As such, the classical elements appear in alchemical writings, as do the seven classical planets and the corresponding seven metals of antiquity.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] Similarly, the gods of the Roman pantheon who are associated with these luminaries are discussed in alchemical literature.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The concepts of prima materia and anima mundi are central to the theory of the philosopher's stone.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p02] The Great Work of Alchemy is often described as a series of four stages represented by colours.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Those focusing on the exoteric, such as historians of science Lawrence M.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Newman, have interpreted the *Decknamen* ('code words') of alchemy as physical substances.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] These scholars have reconstructed physicochemical experiments that they say are described in medieval and early modern texts.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] At the opposite end of the spectrum, focusing on the esoteric, scholars, such as Florin George Călian and Anna Marie Roos, who question the reading of Principe and Newman, interpret these same *Decknamen* as spiritual, religious, or psychological concepts.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] New interpretations of alchemy are still perpetuated, sometimes merging with concepts from New Age or radical environmentalism movements.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Groups like the Rosicrucians and Freemasons have a continued interest in alchemy and its symbolism.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] In the eyes of a variety of modern esoteric and neo-Hermetic practitioners, alchemy is primarily spiritual.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] In this interpretation, transmutation of lead into gold is presented as an analogy for personal transmutation, purification, and perfection.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] According to this view, early alchemists, such as Zosimos of Panopolis (c.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] 300 AD), highlighted the spiritual nature of the alchemical quest, symbolic of a religious regeneration of the human soul.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] This approach is held to have continued in the Middle Ages, as metaphysical aspects, substances, physical states, and material processes are supposed to have been used as metaphors for spiritual entities, spiritual states, and, ultimately, transformation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] In this sense, the literal meanings of alchemical formulas hid a spiritual philosophy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Applied to the alchemist, the twin goal symbolized their evolution from ignorance to enlightenment, and the stone represented a hidden spiritual truth or power that would lead to that goal.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Alchemical symbolism was important in analytical psychology.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] It was revived and popularized from near extinction by the Swiss psychologist Carl Gustav Jung.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] He observed these alchemical images occurring during the psychic process of transformation, a process that Jung called "individuation".
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Specifically, he regarded the conjuring up of images of gold or Lapis as symbolic expressions of the origin and goal of this "process of individuation".
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Together with his alchemical *mystica soror* (mystical sister), Jungian Swiss analyst Marie-Louise von Franz, Jung began collecting old alchemical texts, compiled a lexicon of key phrases with cross-references, and pored over them.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] His writings are influential in general psychology, especially for those interested in understanding the importance of dreams, symbols, and the unconscious archetypal forces (Jungian archetypes) that comprise all psychic life.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Both von Franz and Jung contributed significantly to the subject and work of alchemy and to its continued presence in psychology and contemporary culture.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Among the volumes Jung wrote on alchemy, his magnum opus is volume 14 of his *Collected Works*, *Mysterium Coniunctionis*.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Alchemy has had a long-standing relationship with art, evident in both alchemical texts and mainstream entertainment.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] *Literary alchemy* appears throughout the history of English literature from William Shakespeare to J.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Rowling, and also the popular Japanese manga *Fullmetal Alchemist*.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Here, characters or plot structure follow an alchemical magnum opus.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] In the 14th century, Chaucer began a trend of alchemical satire that can still be seen in recent fantasy works, such as those of the late Sir Terry Pratchett.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Another literary work inspired by the alchemical tradition is the 1988 novel *The Alchemist* by Brazilian writer Paulo Coelho.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Visual artists have had a similar relationship with alchemy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] While some used it as a source of satire, others worked with the alchemists themselves or integrated alchemical thought or symbols in their work.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Music was also present in the works of alchemists and continues to influence popular performers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] In the last hundred years, alchemists have been portrayed in a magical and spagyric role in fantasy fiction, film, television, novels, comics, and video games.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] One goal of alchemy, the transmutation of base substances into gold, is now known to be impossible by means of traditional chemistry, but possible by other physical means.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alchemy-p03] Although not financially worthwhile, gold was synthesized in particle accelerators as early as 1941.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In chemistry, **rotamers** are chemical species that differ from one another primarily due to rotations about one single bond.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Various arrangements of atoms in a molecule that differ by rotation about single bonds can also be referred to as **conformations**.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Conformations, which represent local minima on the potential energy surface, are called **conformers**.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Conformers can differ from one another due to rotation of multiple bonds; rotamers are a subset of conformers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Conformers/rotamers usually differ little in their energies, so they are almost never separable in a practical sense.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Rotations about single bonds are subject to small energy barriers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] When the time scale for interconversion is long enough for isolation of individual rotamers (usually arbitrarily defined as a half-life of interconversion of 1000 seconds or longer), the species are termed atropisomers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The ring-flip of substituted cyclohexanes constitutes a common form of conformers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The study of the energetics of bond rotation is referred to as **conformational analysis**.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In some cases, conformational analysis can be used to predict and explain product selectivity, mechanisms, and rates of reactions.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Conformational analysis also plays an important role in rational, structure-based drug design.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Rotating their carbon–carbon bonds, the molecules ethane and propane have three local energy minima.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] They are structurally and energetically equivalent, and are called the *staggered conformers*.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] For each molecule, the three substituents emanating from each carbon–carbon bond are staggered, with each H–C–C–H dihedral angle (and H–C–C–CH3 dihedral angle in the case of propane) equal to 60° (or approximately equal to 60° in the case of propane).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The three eclipsed conformations, in which the dihedral angles are zero, are transition states (energy maxima) connecting two equivalent energy minima, the staggered conformers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The butane molecule is the simplest molecule for which single bond rotations result in two types of nonequivalent structures, known as the *anti*- and *gauche-*conformers (see figure).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The energy separation between gauche and anti is 0.9 kcal/mol associated with the strain energy of the gauche conformer.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The anti conformer is, therefore, the most stable (≈ 0 kcal/mol).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The three eclipsed conformations with dihedral angles of 0°, 120°, and 240° are transition states between conformers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Note that the two eclipsed conformations have distinct energies: at 0° the two methyl groups are eclipsed, resulting in higher energy (≈ 5 kcal/mol) than at 120°, where the methyl groups are eclipsed with hydrogens (≈ 3.5 kcal/mol).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] A rough approximate function can illustrate the main features of the conformational analysis for unbranched linear alkanes with rotation around a central C–C bond (C1–C2 in ethane, C2–C3 in butane, C3–C4 in hexane, etc.).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The members of this series have the general formula C*2n*H*4n+2* with the index *n = 1, 2, 3,* etc.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] It can be assumed that the angle strain is negligible in alkanes since the bond angles are all near the tetrahedral ideal.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The energy profile is thus periodic with $2\pi /3$ (120°) periodicity due to the threefold symmetry of sp3-hybridized carbon atoms.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] For alkanes, the dominant term is usually $k=3$ , reflecting the threefold rotational symmetry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Higher terms may be included for precision where steric effects vary.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The primary contribution comes from torsional strain due to alkyl groups eclipsing, captured by the $\cos(3\theta )$ term.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Steric interactions rise with the size of substituents (H– for ethane, CH3– for butane, C2H5– for hexane, etc.), taken into account by the $\cos(\theta )$ term $(k=1)$ .
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The number of carbon atoms clearly influences the size of substituents on the central C–C bond.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In general, for unbranched linear alkanes with even-numbered chains, there will be two C*n-1*H*2n-1* group substituents.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Here $V(\theta ,n)$ is given in kcal/mol and $k=1,3$ .
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] This function largely neglects angle strain and long-range interactions for the n members of the series.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] While simple molecules can be described by these types of conformations, more complex molecules require the use of the Klyne–Prelog system to describe the conformers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Three isotherms are given in the diagram depicting the equilibrium distribution of two conformers at various temperatures.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] At a free energy difference of 0 kcal/mol, this analysis gives an equilibrium constant of 1, meaning that two conformers exist in a 1:1 ratio.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The two have equal free energy; neither is more stable, so neither predominates compared to the other.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] A negative difference in free energy means that a conformer interconverts to a thermodynamically more stable conformation, thus the equilibrium constant will always be greater than 1.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] For example, the Δ*G°* for the transformation of butane from the *gauche* conformer to the *anti* conformer is −0.47 kcal/mol at 298 K.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] This gives an equilibrium constant is about 2.2 in favor of the *anti* conformer, or a 31:69 mixture of *gauche*:*anti* conformers at equilibrium.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Conversely, a positive difference in free energy means the conformer already is the more stable one, so the interconversion is an unfavorable equilibrium (*K* < 1).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The left hand side is the proportion of conformer *i* in an equilibrating mixture of *M* conformers in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] On the right side, *E**k* (*k* = 1, 2, ..., *M*) is the energy of conformer *k*, *R* is the molar ideal gas constant (approximately equal to 8.314 J/(mol·K) or 1.987 cal/(mol·K)), and *T* is the absolute temperature.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The denominator of the right side is the partition function.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The effects of electrostatic and steric interactions of the substituents as well as orbital interactions such as hyperconjugation are responsible for the relative stability of conformers and their transition states.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The contributions of these factors vary depending on the nature of the substituents and may either contribute positively or negatively to the energy barrier.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Computational studies of small molecules such as ethane suggest that electrostatic effects make the greatest contribution to the energy barrier; however, the barrier is traditionally attributed primarily to steric interactions.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In the case of cyclic systems, the steric effect and contribution to the free energy can be approximated by A values, which measure the energy difference when a substituent on cyclohexane in the axial as compared to the equatorial position.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In large (>14 atom) rings, there are many accessible low-energy conformations which correspond to the strain-free diamond lattice.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The short timescale of interconversion precludes the separation of conformer in most cases.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Atropisomers are conformational isomers which can be separated due to restricted rotation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The equilibrium between conformational isomers can be observed using a variety of spectroscopic techniques.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Protein folding also generates conformers which can be observed.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The Karplus equation relates the dihedral angle of vicinal protons to their J-coupling constants as measured by NMR.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The equation aids in the elucidation of protein folding as well as the conformations of other rigid aliphatic molecules.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Protein side chains exhibit rotamers, whose distribution is determined by their steric interaction with different conformations of the backbone.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] This effect is evident from statistical analysis of the conformations of protein side chains in the Backbone-dependent rotamer library.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Conformational dynamics can be monitored by variable temperature NMR spectroscopy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The technique applies to barriers of 8–14 kcal/mol, and species exhibiting such dynamics are often called "fluxional".
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] For example, in cyclohexane derivatives, the two chair conformers interconvert rapidly at room temperature.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The ring-flip proceeds at a rates of approximately 105 ring-flips/sec, with an overall energy barrier of 10 kcal/mol (42 kJ/mol).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] This barrier precludes separation at ambient temperatures.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] However, at low temperatures below the coalescence point one can directly monitor the equilibrium by NMR spectroscopy and by dynamic, temperature dependent NMR spectroscopy the barrier interconversion.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Besides NMR spectroscopy, IR spectroscopy is used to measure conformer ratios.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] For the axial and equatorial conformer of bromocyclohexane, νCBr differs by almost 50 cm−1.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Reaction rates are highly dependent on the conformation of the reactants.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In many cases the dominant product arises from the reaction of the *less prevalent* conformer, by virtue of the Curtin-Hammett principle.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] This is typical for situations where the conformational equilibration is much faster than reaction to form the product.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The dependence of a reaction on the stereochemical orientation is therefore usually only visible in configurational analysis, in which a particular conformation is locked by substituents.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Prediction of rates of many reactions involving the transition between sp2 and sp3 states, such as ketone reduction, alcohol oxidation or nucleophilic substitution is possible if all conformers and their relative stability ruled by their strain is taken into account.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] One example where the rotamers become significant is elimination reactions, which involve the simultaneous removal of a proton and a leaving group from vicinal or *anti*periplanar positions under the influence of a base.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The mechanism requires that the departing atoms or groups follow antiparallel trajectories.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] For open chain substrates this geometric prerequisite is met by at least one of the three staggered conformers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] For some cyclic substrates such as cyclohexane, however, an antiparallel arrangement may not be attainable depending on the substituents which might set a conformational lock.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Adjacent substituents on a cyclohexane ring can achieve antiperiplanarity only when they occupy trans diaxial positions (that is, both are in axial position, one going up and one going down).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The thermodynamically unfavored conformation has the *t*-Bu group in the axial position, which is higher in energy by more than 5 kcal/mol (see A value).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] As a result, the *t*-Bu group "locks" the ring in the conformation where it is in the equatorial position and substitution reaction is observed.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] On the other hand, *cis*-4-*tert*-butylcyclohexyl chloride undergoes elimination because antiperiplanarity of Cl and H can be achieved when the *t*-Bu group is in the favorable equatorial position.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] isomer can attain antiperiplanarity only via the unfavored axial conformer; therefore, it does not eliminate.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] isomer is already in the correct geometry in its most stable conformation; therefore, it eliminates easily.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The repulsion between an axial *t*-butyl group and hydrogen atoms in the 1,3-diaxial position is so strong that the cyclohexane ring will revert to a twisted boat conformation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The strain in cyclic structures is usually characterized by deviations from ideal bond angles (Baeyer strain), ideal torsional angles (Pitzer strain) or transannular (Prelog) interactions.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Alkane conformers arise from rotation around sp3 hybridised carbon–carbon sigma bonds.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The smallest alkane with such a chemical bond, ethane, exists as an infinite number of conformations with respect to rotation around the C–C bond.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Two of these are recognised as energy minimum (staggered conformation) and energy maximum (eclipsed conformation) forms.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The existence of specific conformations is due to hindered rotation around sigma bonds, although a role for hyperconjugation is proposed by a competing theory.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The importance of energy minima and energy maxima is seen by extension of these concepts to more complex molecules for which stable conformations may be predicted as minimum-energy forms.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The determination of stable conformations has also played a large role in the establishment of the concept of asymmetric induction and the ability to predict the stereochemistry of reactions controlled by steric effects.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In the example of staggered ethane in Newman projection, a hydrogen atom on one carbon atom has a 60° **torsional angle** or **torsion angle** with respect to the nearest hydrogen atom on the other carbon so that steric hindrance is minimised.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The staggered conformation is more stable by 12.5 kJ/mol than the eclipsed conformation, which is the energy maximum for ethane.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In the eclipsed conformation the torsional angle is minimised.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In butane, the two staggered conformations are no longer equivalent and represent two distinct conformers:the **anti-conformation** (left-most, below) and the **gauche conformation** (right-most, below).
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Both conformations are free of torsional strain, but, in the gauche conformation, the two methyl groups are in closer proximity than the sum of their van der Waals radii.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The interaction between the two methyl groups is repulsive (van der Waals strain), and an energy barrier results.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The eclipsed methyl groups exert a greater steric strain because of their greater electron density compared to lone hydrogen atoms.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The textbook explanation for the existence of the energy maximum for an eclipsed conformation in ethane is steric hindrance, but, with a C-C bond length of 154 pm and a Van der Waals radius for hydrogen of 120 pm, the hydrogen atoms in ethane are never in each other's way.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The question of whether steric hindrance is responsible for the eclipsed energy maximum is a topic of debate to this day.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] One alternative to the steric hindrance explanation is based on hyperconjugation as analyzed within the Natural Bond Orbital framework.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In the staggered conformation, one C-H sigma bonding orbital donates electron density to the antibonding orbital of the other C-H bond.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] The energetic stabilization of this effect is maximized when the two orbitals have maximal overlap, occurring in the staggered conformation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] There is no overlap in the eclipsed conformation, leading to a disfavored energy maximum.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] On the other hand, an analysis within quantitative molecular orbital theory shows that 2-orbital-4-electron (steric) repulsions are dominant over hyperconjugation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] A valence bond theory study also emphasizes the importance of steric effects.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Torsional strain or "Pitzer strain" refers to resistance to twisting about a bond.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] In *n*-pentane, the terminal methyl groups experience additional pentane interference.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Replacing hydrogen by fluorine in polytetrafluoroethylene changes the stereochemistry from the zigzag geometry to that of a helix due to electrostatic repulsion of the fluorine atoms in the 1,3 positions.
[src:microscale-chemistry/alkane-stereochemistry] Evidence for the helix structure in the crystalline state is derived from X-ray crystallography and from NMR spectroscopy and circular dichroism in solution.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Amateur chemistry shares its early history with that of chemistry in general.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Pioneers of modern chemistry such as Robert Boyle and Antoine Lavoisier were gentlemen scientists who pursued their research independently from their source of income.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Only with the coming of the Industrial Revolution, and the rise of universities as research institutions, did any significant distinction between amateurs and professionals emerge.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Nevertheless, amateur progress lasted well into the 19th century.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] For example, in 1886, Charles Martin Hall co-invented the Hall-Héroult process for extracting aluminium from its oxide whilst working in a woodshed behind his family home.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] The history of amateur chemistry ties in well with that of chemistry in general.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] The history of chemistry represents a time span from ancient history to the present.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] By 1000 BC, civilizations used technologies that would eventually form the basis to the various branches of chemistry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] These processes include extracting metals from ores, making pottery and glazes, fermenting beer and wine, extracting chemicals from plants for medicine and perfume, rendering fat into soap, making glass, and making alloys like bronze.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Throughout much of the 20th century, amateur chemistry was an unexceptional hobby, with high-quality chemistry sets readily available, and laboratory suppliers freely selling to hobbyists.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] For example, Linus Pauling had no difficulty in procuring potassium cyanide at the age of eleven.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Many academics, from researchers to university professors, and even Nobel prize laureates, have acknowledged that at least part of their interest in sciences could be traced back to chemistry sets and home labs when they were young.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] These include Dorothy Hodgkin, Robert F.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Phillips, Steven Weinberg, Peter Licence, etc.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] However, due to increasing concerns about terrorism, drugs, and safety, suppliers became increasingly reluctant to sell to amateurs, and chemistry sets were steadily toned down.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] This trend has gradually continued, leaving hobbyists in many parts of the world without access to most reagents.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Even as recently as 2023, amateur chemists on forums and YouTube channels have been credited by academic researchers for suggesting and discussing novel viable synthetic routes before full investigations by the latter.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Home-based chemistry labs were explored as a way to remotely teach students during the COVID-19 pandemic, especially since many local and state-level governments across the world imposed lockdowns or other types of restrictions to contain the spread of the virus.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Whilst the hobby is probably legal in most jurisdictions,[b] the relationship between amateur chemists and law enforcement agencies is often fraught.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Hobbyists are often affected by laws intended to fight drugs and terrorism.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Furthermore, many chemical supply houses refuse to sell to amateurs, with such policies sometimes being stated openly.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Medium-sized suppliers and multinationals have whole departments, sometimes named Compliance or Regulatory affairs, tasked with periodically checking and implementing new regulations regarding chemicals on their companies.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] In Canada, a wide range of basic laboratory reagents such as nitric acid and hydrogen peroxide are restricted as "explosives precursors".
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Two of the main legal texts in Canada restricting the sale of certain chemicals are the Explosives Act, and the Explosives Regulations, 2013 (SOR/2013-211).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] In late 2008, Lewis Casey, an 18-year-old college student from Saskatchewan, was arrested for owning a small chemistry lab in his family's garage.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] After the raid, the police initially claimed that it was a meth lab, but withdrew the drug charge a few days later.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] The Crown withdrew criminal charges against him on Oct.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Those regulations may contain provisions affecting one or more types of "agents" (e.g. manufacturers, resellers, distributors, etc.), end users, or both.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Reagent manufacturers typically require customers to sign an end user declaration before accepting and processing the sale of a chemical listed on these schedules.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] One of the cornerstones of EU legislation on hazardous chemicals is the Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals (REACH), which is defined in Regulation (EC) No.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] On the topic of explosives precursors, Regulation (EU) No.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] 98/2013 introduced rules to harmonize the sale, possession and use of several substances across all EU countries.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] It requires that each member state must define a National Contact Point to which economic operators must report suspicious transactions, thefts, and disappearances of significant quantities involving scheduled substances.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] On 1 February 2021, Regulation (EU) 2019/1148 amended REACH and repealed Regulation (EC) No.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] The newer one is designed to ban the sale and possession of explosives precursors by members of the general public above given concentrations.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Any individual can own these chemicals provided their concentration is below or equal to a given limit (e.g. for sulfuric acid up to 15% conc. in weight).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Said upper limit allowed can be increased (e.g. for sulfuric acid, up to 40% conc.) by requesting a license to the national authority.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Professional users are not affected by these thresholds.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] However, professional users and members of the general public must also report significant disappearances and thefts of restricted explosives precursors within 24 hours of detection to the national contact point.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Regarding waste management, it might be considered acceptable to dispose of some acidic or basic solutions by neutralizing and flushing them down the drain, provided that they don't contain other hazardous substances and the reaction products aren't hazardous either.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] However, other types of wastes must be disposed by handling them to an authorised waste management entity in an appropriate container, usually HDPE jerry cans.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Such entities require each container received to be appropriately labeled with several details, which may include GHS hazard pictograms, the EWC (European Waste Catalogue) code, also called LoW (List of Waste) code, that identifies the type of waste.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] These codes were defined by the Commission Decision 2000/532/EC, later amended by Commission Decision 2014/955/EU.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Several chemicals, especially solvents, are subject to taxes for certain uses.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] One such example is ethanol, due to its potential use in alcoholic drinks.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Both Council Directive 92/81/EEC, and Council Directive 2003/96/EC, which repealed the former, impose taxes on several hydrocarbons that can be used as fuels.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Regulations regarding hazardous chemicals in this country include the Explosives Act (Sprengstoffgesetz), and the Hazardous Substances Ordinance (Gefahrstoffverordnung, abbreviated as GefStoffV), which is part of the Chemicals Act (Chemikaliengesetz, abbreviated as ChemG).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Another one is the Chemicals Prohibition Ordinance (Chemikalien-Verbotsverordnung, abbreviated as ChemVerbotsV).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Additionally, Regulation (EU) 2019/1148 was transposed into German law in the Precursor Act (Ausgangsstoffgesetz, Precursor Act, abbreviated as AusgStG).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] German amateur chemists have been raided by the police, despite not being in the possession of illegal chemicals.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Regarding explosives precursors, Regulation (EU) 98/2013, was transposed in the Statutory Instrument No 611/2014.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] In Italy, regulations regarding explosives precursors have been approved as the Ministry of the Interior's Circolare 557/PAS/U/004997/XV.H.MASS(53)5, titled Identificazione e tracciabilità degli esplosivi per uso civile: - Indicazioni operative e gestione delle scorte.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Regulation (EU) 2019/1148 was implemented through the Legge 23 dicembre 2021, n.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] 238, whose article 13 modifies the Decreto Legislativo 14 settembre 2009, n.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] 133, adding a whole chapter to the latter (Chapter II, after article 17).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] On the topic of explosives precursors, Regulation (EU) 98/2013, was transposed into the Portuguese legal system as the Decree Law 56/2016, of 29th of August.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] This Decree Law was, in turn, repealed by Decree Law 62/2021, of 26th of July, which transposes Regulation (EU) 2019/1148.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] On January 3, 1994, Eduardo Rey Díaz, a 13-year-old boy from Getxo, Basque Country, was at a friend's house doing an experiment using materials from a chemistry set.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] After approaching the open end of a graduated cylinder containing a flammable substance to an open flame, a deflagration occurred, which left him with severe burns in his hands and face.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] The manufacturer was sued and later fined.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Less than a year and a half later, in December 22, 1995, an 11-year-old boy and his 8-year-old sister from Galicia, suffered third and second-degree burns in 70 and 60% of their bodies.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] After watching them while they performed an experiment using another set from the same company, their mother ordered them to put the game away and left the room, but they kept playing.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] As a result of incorrectly handling the set, a deflagration occurred, and the company was sued and charged again.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] By the 2010s, many of them were no longer available.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Despite these incidents, the positive impact of chemistry sets on kickstarting the curiosity of children, some of whom would later become professional scientists and engineers, has been acknowledged.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] According to the Resolution of 20 November 2013 of the Spanish State Secretariat for Security, the National Contact Point for this country is the Intelligence Center for Counter-Terrorism and Organized Crime (CITCO).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Before the transposition of Regulation (EU) 2019/1148 into Spanish Law 25/2022, of 1st of November, explosives precursors were addressed by Law 8/2017, of 8 November, on explosives precursors, which the former repealed and replaced.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] On the other hand, drug precursors are addressed by the Law 4/2009, of 15 June, on drug precursors control, and the Royal Decree 129/2017, of 24 February, by which the Drug Precursors Control Regulation is approved.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] The first ones (purchases and sales) must include information on the quantities, full contact details and address, and NIF or DNI number of the suppliers or buyers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Additionally, the storage of chemicals, including reagents, flammable solvents, and gas cylinders, is regulated by Royal Decree 656/2017, of 23 June.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Industrial establishments also need to take into account Royal Decree 2267/2004, of 3 December, by which the fire safety regulations for industrial establishments are approved.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] In general, the topic of *hazardous waste management* is discussed on Law 22/2011, of 28 July, on wastes and contaminated soils, which was repealed and replaced by Law 7/2022, of 8 April.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] The transport of wastes is regulated as well, by the Royal Decree 553/2020, of 2 June.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Business that meet the definition of 'waste producers' or 'waste management facilities' need to obtain an Environmental Identification Number (Número de identificación medioambiental, NIMA).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Said numbers are issued by the government of the autonomous community where the business is located.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Several EU regulations regarding special taxes have been transposed to Spanish regulations in Law 38/1992, of 28 December, of Special Taxes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] It was later extended by the Royal Decree 1165/1995, of 7 July, by which the Regulation on Special Taxes is approved.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] According to article 79 of the latter, even though ethanol is subject to a special tax due to its potential use in spirits, its use in scientific research can be exempted.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] This exemption requires obtaining an Activity and Establishment Code (Código de Actividad y del Establecimiento, CAE), which allows to request a refund from the Tax Agency (Agencia Tributaria) by submitting a filled form model 572.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Said code is composed of 13 characters, the first two being "ES", then three zeros, two characters identifying the local management office, two more characters for the activity, a sequential inscription number made up of three characters, and finally a control letter.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] A refund can also be requested for the special tax on hydrocarbons as long as they aren't used as fuels, according to article 109 the same Royal Decree (1165/1995, of 7 July).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] One of the laws regulating chemicals in Sweden is the Act on flammable and explosive goods (Lag om brandfarliga och explosiva varor).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] In September 2018, a 29-year-old physician and amateur chemist and his girlfriend were arrested at their home on in Nord-Jæren, two days after inquiring a local pharmacy about the availability of 35% hydrogen peroxide.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] He explained that he had an accident while camping, suffering a wound that he stitched himself.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Being a physician and seeing the effect of flame-sterilizing on his surgical instruments, he was looking for a milder alternative that could also be used to disinfect wounds.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] However, his enquiry triggered the submission of an alert to KRIPOS, which sent a few police officers to the house.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] These officers would, in turn, find the chemicals from his lab, and arrest him.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] One law in this country that regulates flammable chemicals, gas cylinders, and explosive substances is the Fire and Explosion Protection Act (Brann- og eksplosjonsvernloven).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] In the UK it is a criminal offence for members of the general public to purchase, and for business to sell, certain types of poisons or explosives precursors to those of the former group without a valid EPP license.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Purchasing substances on this list is restricted since 26 May 2015, and its possession is also restricted since 3 March 2016.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Since July 1st 2018, the acquisition of sulphuric acid in concentrations above 15% in weight by members of the general public also requires an EPP licence, which has impacted lead-acid battery sellers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] On 26 February 2022, three men, aged between 20 and 25, were arrested in Wigan on suspicions they had violated Section 4 of the Explosives Act.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] A search warrant had found several chemicals on their flat.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Soon after, the eldest was released on bail, and the other two were also released under investigation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Two years later, in May 2024, the investigation concluded that they had just been doing amateur chemistry, and none of the three were charged.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Some regulations regarding restricted chemicals in this country include the Poison Act 1972, which was amended by the Deregulation Act 2015, and the Control of Poisons and Explosives Precursors Regulations 2015.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] On 1 October 2023, a new set of amendments to the Poisons Act 1972, known as the "Control of Poisons and Explosives Precursors Regulations 2023", came into force.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] The sulfides of aluminium, calcium, magnesium, sodium and zinc, as well as arsenic and its compounds are now considered "regulated poisons" rather than just "reportable poisons".
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Finally, sulfur, all metal phosphides, all metal sulfides, all metal polysulfides and sodium hypochlorite solutions above 6% available chlorine have been added to the "reportable poisons" list.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Directly related to the above is the Offensive Weapons Act 2019, which forbids the sale of corrosive chemicals to minors, as well as their shipment to residential addresses or lockers.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] In the United States, the Drug Enforcement Administration maintains lists regarding the classification of illicit drugs, which contain chemicals that are used to manufacture the controlled substances/illicit drugs.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] The lists are designated within The Controlled Substances Act, 21 U.S.C. § 802, paragraphs 34 (list I) and 35 (list II).
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Additionally, some regions have stringent regulations concerning the ownership of chemicals and equipment.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] For example, Texas once required the registration of even the most basic laboratory glassware.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] However, this requirement was repealed on June 6, 2019.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Several states define hazardous waste management laws, one example being the California Hazardous Waste Control Law (Cal.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Passed in 2017, California Assembly Bill (AB) 245 raised the maximum administrative and civil penalties for violations of said law from $25,000 per day of noncompliance to $70,000 per day.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] United Nuclear, an amateur science supplier based in New Mexico was raided in June 2003 at the behest of the U.S.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Consumer Product Safety Commission, and subsequently fined $7,500 for "Selling Illegal Fireworks Components".
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Almost a year later, Jack Robison, then a 19-year-old chemistry student at the Holyoke Community College, received a visit from members of the Massachusetts State Police, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives, and the FBI.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] They asked him questions regarding several videos on small-scale experiments he had posted two years earlier on YouTube involving energetic materials, including PETN, potassium nitrate, and RDX, and wanted to check his mother's house basement.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] He was initially charged with three counts of malicious explosion and one count of possessing explosives with the intent to harm people or property, facing up to 60 years in prison, but was found not guilty after trial.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Amateur chemistry has been depicted multiple times in mass media, through different formats.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] The protagonists or other characters of animated television series like Dexter's Laboratory, Tracey McBean and The Simpsons (e.g. on the Haw-Haw Land episode) are sometimes displayed performing chemistry experiments in their own laboratories.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] On the other hand, there are several YouTube channels focused in chemical experiments.
[src:microscale-chemistry/amateur-chemistry] Most of them are run by amateurs, mostly by professional communicators and organizations, though there are a small sample of professional chemists.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] It encompasses both classical techniques (e.g. titration, gravimetric analysis) and modern instrumental approaches (e.g. spectroscopy, chromatography, mass spectrometry, electrochemical methods).
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] There is also a strong trend towards miniaturization, automation, and the development of real-time, point-of-care diagnostic sensors.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has been important since the early days of chemistry, providing methods for determining which elements and chemicals are present in the object in question.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] During this period, significant contributions to analytical chemistry included the development of systematic elemental analysis by Justus von Liebig and systematized organic analysis based on the specific reactions of functional groups.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The first instrumental analysis was flame emissive spectrometry, developed by Robert Bunsen and Gustav Kirchhoff, who discovered rubidium (Rb) and caesium (Cs) in 1860.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Most of the major developments in analytical chemistry took place after 1900.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] During this period, instrumental analysis became progressively dominant in the field.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In particular, many of the basic spectroscopic and spectrometric techniques were discovered in the early 20th century and refined in the late 20th century.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The separation sciences follow a similar timeline of development and have also became increasingly transformed into high-performance instruments.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In the 1970s many of these techniques began to be used together as hybrid techniques to achieve a complete characterization of samples.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Starting in the 1970s, analytical chemistry became progressively more inclusive of biological questions (bioanalytical chemistry), whereas it had previously been largely focused on inorganic or small organic molecules.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Lasers have been increasingly used as probes and even to initiate and influence a wide variety of reactions.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The late 20th century also saw an expansion of the application of analytical chemistry from somewhat academic chemical questions to forensic, environmental, industrial and medical questions, such as in histology.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Modern analytical chemistry is dominated by instrumental analysis.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Many analytical chemists focus on a single type of instrument.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Academics tend to either focus on new applications and discoveries or on new methods of analysis.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The discovery of a chemical present in blood that increases the risk of cancer would be a discovery that an analytical chemist might be involved in.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] An effort to develop a new method might involve the use of a tunable laser to increase the specificity and sensitivity of a spectrometric method.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Many methods, once developed, are kept purposely static so that data can be compared over long periods of time.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] This is particularly true in industrial quality assurance (QA), forensic, and environmental applications.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry plays an increasingly important role in the pharmaceutical industry where, aside from QA, it is used in the discovery of new drug candidates and in clinical applications where understanding the interactions between the drug and the patient are critical.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The 21st century has been defined by the digitalization of analytical chemistry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The handling of large datasets ("big data") from instruments like Orbitrap mass spectrometers has made advanced data analysis, including machine learning, an essential skill.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] This era also focuses strongly on sustainability, leading to the green chemistry subfield of Green Analytical Chemistry, which aims to minimize the environmental impact of chemical analyses.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Although modern analytical chemistry is dominated by sophisticated instrumentation, the roots of analytical chemistry and some of the principles used in modern instruments are from traditional techniques, many of which are still used today.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] These techniques also tend to form the backbone of most undergraduate analytical chemistry educational labs.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] There are numerous qualitative chemical tests; examples include the acid test for gold and the Kastle-Meyer test for the presence of blood.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Inorganic qualitative analysis generally refers to a systematic scheme to confirm the presence of certain aqueous ions or elements by performing a series of reactions that eliminate a range of possibilities and then confirm suspected ions with a confirming test.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Sometimes small carbon-containing ions are included in such schemes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] With modern instrumentation, these tests are rarely used but can be useful for educational purposes and in fieldwork or other situations where access to state-of-the-art instruments is not available or expedient.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Quantitative analysis is the measurement of the quantities of particular chemical constituents present in a substance.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Quantities can be measured by mass (gravimetric analysis) or volume (volumetric analysis).
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Gravimetric analysis involves determining the amount of material present by weighing the sample before and/or after some transformation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] A common example used in undergraduate education is the determination of the amount of water in a hydrate by heating the sample to remove the water such that the difference in weight is due to the loss of water.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Titration involves the gradual addition of a measurable reactant to an exact volume of a solution being analyzed until some equivalence point is reached.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Titration is a family of techniques used to determine the concentration of an analyte.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Titrating accurately to either the half-equivalence point or the endpoint of a titration allows the chemist to determine the amount of moles used, which can then be used to determine a concentration or composition of the titrant.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Most familiar to those who have taken chemistry during secondary education is the acid-base titration involving a color-changing pH indicator, such as phenolphthalein.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] There are many other types of titrations, including potentiometric titrations and precipitation titrations.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Chemists might also create titration curves by systematically testing the pH after every added drop in order to understand different properties of the titrant.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Spectroscopy measures the interaction of the molecules with electromagnetic radiation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Mass spectrometry measures mass-to-charge ratio of molecules using electric and magnetic fields.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In a mass spectrometer, a small amount of sample is ionized and converted to gaseous ions, where they are separated and analyzed according to their mass-to-charge ratios.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] There are several ionization methods: electron ionization, chemical ionization, electrospray ionization, fast atom bombardment, matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization, and others.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Also, mass spectrometry is categorized by approaches of mass analyzers: magnetic-sector, quadrupole mass analyzer, quadrupole ion trap, time-of-flight, Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance, and so on.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Electroanalytical methods measure the potential (volts) and/or current (amps) in an electrochemical cell containing the analyte.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] These methods can be categorized according to which aspects of the cell are controlled and which are measured.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Calorimetry and thermogravimetric analysis measure the interaction of a material and heat.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Separation processes are used to decrease the complexity of material mixtures.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Chromatography, electrophoresis and field flow fractionation are representative of this field.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Chromatography can be used to determine the presence of substances in a sample, as different components in a mixture have different tendencies to adsorb onto the stationary phase or dissolve in the mobile phase.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Thus, different components of the mixture move at different speeds.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Different components of a mixture can therefore be identified by their respective R*ƒ* values, which is the ratio between the migration distance of the substance and the migration distance of the solvent front during chromatography.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In combination with the instrumental methods, chromatography can be used in the quantitative determination of substances.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] There are different types of chromatography that differ from the media they use to separate the analyte and the sample.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In thin-layer chromatography, the analyte mixture moves up and separates along the coated sheet under the volatile mobile phase.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In gas chromatography, the gas phase separates the volatile analytes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] A common method of chromatography using liquid as a mobile phase is high-performance liquid chromatography.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Combinations of the above techniques produce a "hybrid" or "hyphenated" technique.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Several examples are in popular use today and new hybrid techniques are under development.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] For example, gas chromatography-mass spectrometry, gas chromatography-infrared spectroscopy, liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry, liquid chromatography-NMR spectroscopy, liquid chromatography-infrared spectroscopy, and capillary electrophoresis-mass spectrometry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Hyphenated separation techniques refer to a combination of two (or more) techniques to detect and separate chemicals from solutions.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Most often the other technique is some form of chromatography.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Hyphenated techniques are widely used in chemistry and biochemistry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] A slash is sometimes used instead of hyphen, especially if the name of one of the methods contains a hyphen itself.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The visualization of single molecules, single cells, biological tissues, and nanomaterials is an important and attractive approach in analytical science.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Also, hybridization with other traditional analytical tools is revolutionizing analytical science.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Microscopy can be categorized into three different fields: optical microscopy, electron microscopy, and scanning probe microscopy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Recently, this field is rapidly progressing because of the rapid development of the computer and camera industries.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Devices that integrate (multiple) laboratory functions on a single chip of only millimeters to a few square centimeters in size and that are capable of handling extremely small fluid volumes down to less than picoliters.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The vast amount of data produced by modern analytical instruments has made computational data analysis an integral part of the field.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The field of chemometrics uses statistical and mathematical methods to design optimal experimental procedures and to extract meaningful information from chemical data.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Error can be defined as numerical difference between observed value and true value.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The experimental error can be divided into two types, systematic error and random error.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Systematic error results from a flaw in equipment or the design of an experiment while random error results from uncontrolled or uncontrollable variables in the experiment.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] An error of a measurement is an inverse measure of accurate measurement (i.e., smaller the error greater the accuracy of the measurement).
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] To use these values in a function, it may be useful to calculate the error of the function.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] A general method for analysis of concentration involves the creation of a calibration curve.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] This allows for the determination of the amount of a chemical in a material by comparing the results of an unknown sample to those of a series of known standards.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] If the concentration of an element or compound in a sample exceeds the detection range of the technique, it can simply be diluted in a pure solvent.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] If the amount in the sample is below an instrument's range of measurement, the method of addition can be used.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In this method, a known quantity of the element or compound under study is added, and the difference between the concentration added and the concentration observed is the amount actually in the sample.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Sometimes an internal standard is added at a known concentration directly to an analytical sample to aid in quantitation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The amount of analyte present is then determined relative to the internal standard as a calibrant.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] An ideal internal standard is an isotopically enriched analyte which gives rise to the method of isotope dilution.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The method of standard addition is used in instrumental analysis to determine the concentration of a substance (analyte) in an unknown sample by comparison to a set of samples of known concentration, similar to using a calibration curve.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Standard addition can be applied to most analytical techniques and is used instead of a calibration curve to solve the matrix effect problem.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] One of the most important components of analytical chemistry is maximizing the desired signal while minimizing the associated noise.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The analytical figure of merit is known as the signal-to-noise ratio (S/N or SNR).
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Noise can arise from environmental factors as well as from fundamental physical processes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Thermal noise results from the motion of charge carriers (usually electrons) in an electrical circuit generated by their thermal motion.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Thermal noise is white noise, meaning that the power spectral density is constant throughout the frequency spectrum.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] where *k*B is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the temperature, *R* is the resistance, and $\Delta f$ is the bandwidth of the frequency f .
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Shot noise is a type of electronic noise that occurs when the finite number of particles (such as electrons in an electronic circuit or photons in an optical device) is small enough to give rise to statistical fluctuations in a signal.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Shot noise is a Poisson process, and the charge carriers that make up the current follow a Poisson distribution.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] where *e* is the elementary charge and *I* is the average current.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Flicker noise is electronic noise with a 1/*ƒ* frequency spectrum; as *f* increases, the noise decreases.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Flicker noise arises from a variety of sources, such as impurities in a conductive channel, generation, and recombination noise in a transistor due to base current, and so on.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] This noise can be avoided by modulation of the signal at a higher frequency, for example, through the use of a lock-in amplifier.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Environmental noise arises from the surroundings of the analytical instrument.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Sources of electromagnetic noise are power lines, radio and television stations, wireless devices, compact fluorescent lamps and electric motors.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Many of these noise sources are narrow bandwidth and, therefore, can be avoided.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Temperature and vibration isolation may be required for some instruments.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Noise reduction can be accomplished either in computer hardware or software.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Examples of hardware noise reduction are the use of shielded cable, analog filtering, and signal modulation.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Examples of software noise reduction are digital filtering, ensemble average, boxcar average, and correlation methods.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has applications across science and industry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Great effort is being put into shrinking the analysis techniques to chip size.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Although few examples of such systems compete with traditional analysis techniques, potential advantages include size/portability, speed, and cost.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Micro total analysis system (μTAS) or lab-on-a-chip.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Microscale chemistry reduces the amount of chemicals used.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Many developments improve the analysis of biological systems.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has played a critical role in the understanding of basic science to a variety of practical applications, such as biomedical applications, environmental monitoring, quality control of industrial manufacturing, and forensic science.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The recent developments in computer automation and information technologies have extended analytical chemistry into several new biological fields.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] For example, automated DNA sequencing machines were the basis for completing human genome projects, leading to the birth of genomics.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Protein identification and peptide sequencing by mass spectrometry opened a new field of proteomics.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In addition to automating specific processes, there is effort to automate larger sections of lab testing, such as in companies like Emerald Cloud Lab and Transcriptic.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has been an indispensable area in the development of nanotechnology.
[src:microscale-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Surface characterization instruments, electron microscopes and scanning probe microscopes enable scientists to visualize atomic structures with chemical characterizations.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] As an offshoot of astronomy and chemistry, the history of astrochemistry follows the development of both fields.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Advances in observational and experimental spectroscopy enabled the detection of an ever‑growing range of molecules within planetary systems and the surrounding interstellar medium.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] The expanding inventory of detected species, made possible by improvements in spectroscopy and related technologies, has in turn broadened the chemical space accessible to astrochemical research.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Early observations of solar spectra by Athanasius Kircher (1646), Jan Marek Marci (1648), Robert Boyle (1664), and Francesco Maria Grimaldi (1665) predated Isaac Newton’s 1666 demonstration of the spectral nature of light, which led to the first spectroscope.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Spectroscopy was first applied to astronomy in 1802, when William Hyde Wollaston used a spectrometer to observe dark lines in the solar spectrum.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] These features were later measured in detail by Joseph von Fraunhofer.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] In 1835, Charles Wheatstone showed that different metals produce distinct emission spectra when sparked, demonstrating that spectral lines could be used to identify chemical elements.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Subsequent work by Léon Foucault (1849) and Anders Jonas Ångström (1853) established that the same material produces identical absorption and emission lines, laying the foundation for chemical identification through spectroscopy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] The theoretical significance of these observations increased with Johann Balmer’s discovery that the spectral lines of hydrogen follow a simple empirical pattern, now known as the Balmer series.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] This relationship was later generalized by the Rydberg formula developed by Johannes Rydberg in 1888, enabling the calculation of spectral lines for many elements.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] With the advent of quantum mechanics, these empirical laws could be derived from first principles, allowing atomic and molecular spectra to be predicted *a priori* and providing the theoretical framework that underpins modern astrochemical spectroscopy.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Although radio astronomy emerged in the 1930s, the first substantial evidence for an interstellar *molecule* was not obtained until 1937, when Swings and Rosenfeld identified spectral features attributable to molecular species.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Until this point, only atomic species were known to exist in interstellar space.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] The result was confirmed in 1940, when McKellar *et al.* attributed previously unidentified spectroscopic lines to CH and CN molecules in the interstellar medium.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Over the following three decades, additional interstellar molecules were detected.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Among the most significant were OH, discovered in 1963 and important as a source of interstellar oxygen, and H2CO (formaldehyde), detected in 1969 and notable as the first observed organic, polyatomic molecule in interstellar space.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] The detection of formaldehyde—and later other molecules with potential biological relevance, such as water and carbon monoxide—was interpreted by some researchers as supporting abiogenetic hypotheses in which the basic molecular components of life may originate in space.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] These discoveries occurred alongside the broader development of modern astrochemical research.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] One of the most important experimental tools in astrochemistry is spectroscopy, which uses telescopes to measure the absorption and emission of light from atoms and molecules in different astrophysical environments.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] By comparing astronomical observations with laboratory spectra, astrochemists can infer the elemental abundances, chemical composition and temperatures of stars and interstellar clouds.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] This is possible because ions, atoms and molecules have characteristic spectra: that is, they absorb and emit light at specific wavelengths, many of which are not visible to the human eye.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Different regions of the electromagnetic spectrum (radio, infrared, visible, ultraviolet and others) probe different types of transitions and are therefore sensitive to different kinds of species.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Perhaps the most powerful technique for detecting individual chemical species in the interstellar medium is radio astronomy, which has revealed more than a hundred interstellar species, including radicals, ions and organic (i.e. carbon-based) molecules such as aldehydes and ketones.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] One of the most abundant interstellar molecules, and among the easiest to detect with radio waves due to its strong electric dipole moment, is CO (carbon monoxide).
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] CO is so common and bright that it is widely used to map molecular regions in galaxies.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] The first organic molecule detected in the interstellar medium by radio techniques was interstellar formaldehyde, which opened up the study of interstellar organic chemistry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] One of the most discussed radio detections is the claimed observation of interstellar glycine, the simplest amino acid, a result that remains controversial.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Radio and related techniques such as rotational spectroscopy are particularly effective for identifying relatively simple species with large dipole moments, but are less sensitive to more complex molecules, even those only modestly larger than amino acids.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Infrared astronomy probes vibrational transitions in molecules, and is especially useful for detecting a wide range of organic and inorganic species.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Many organic compounds absorb and emit strongly in the infrared, so IR spectroscopy is used both for interstellar molecules and for planetary atmospheres.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] For example, the detection of methane in the atmosphere of Mars was achieved using a ground-based IR telescope, NASA's 3-meter Infrared Telescope Facility atop Mauna Kea, Hawaii.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] NASA has also used the airborne IR telescope SOFIA and the space-based Spitzer for astrochemical observations.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Infrared spectroscopy has revealed that the interstellar medium contains a suite of complex gas-phase carbon compounds called polyaromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs or PACs).
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] These molecules, composed primarily of fused rings of carbon (in neutral or ionized states), are thought to be the most common class of carbon compound in the Galaxy and are abundant in cosmic dust, meteorites, and cometary and asteroidal material.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Many of these compounds, along with amino acids, nucleobases and other organics in meteorites, are enriched in deuterium and rare isotopes of carbon, nitrogen and oxygen, indicating an extraterrestrial origin.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] PAHs are thought to form in hot circumstellar environments around dying, carbon-rich red giant stars.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Infrared observations have also been used to assess the composition of solid materials in the interstellar medium, including silicates, kerogen-like carbon-rich solids and ices.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Unlike visible light, which is strongly scattered or absorbed by solid particles, IR radiation can pass through microscopic interstellar grains but is absorbed at specific wavelengths characteristic of their composition.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Some key astrochemical species are more readily detected at ultraviolet or visible wavelengths.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] The most abundant molecule in the universe, H2 (hydrogen gas, or dihydrogen), has no permanent dipole moment and is therefore invisible to radio telescopes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] However, it can be observed in the UV and visible through its characteristic absorption and emission features, including the hydrogen line.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Ultraviolet and visible observations complement radio and infrared measurements by probing different excitation conditions and tracing species that are otherwise difficult to detect.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] All spectroscopic techniques face important limitations.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Radio and rotational spectroscopy are blind to molecules without a dipole moment, such as H2, and in general are less sensitive to large, complex molecules.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Spectroscopic methods that rely on gas-phase transitions also cannot detect species that are frozen onto grains.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] In dense molecular clouds, where temperatures are typically 10 to 50 K [−263.1 to −223.2 °C; −441.7 to −369.7 °F], most molecules other than dihydrogen are in the solid phase, forming thin ice mantles on dust particles.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] In these ices, the initial chemistry is controlled by the available hydrogen: atomic hydrogen tends to produce "reduced" species such as H2O, CH4 and NH3, whereas largely molecular hydrogen allows heavier atoms to form species such as CO, CO2 and CN.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] These mixed-molecular ices are processed by ultraviolet radiation and cosmic rays, driving complex radiation-induced chemistry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Results from the analysis of organics in samples returned by the Stardust mission support such links, while also indicating a substantial contribution from high-temperature chemistry in the solar nebula.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Astrochemical research investigates how molecules form, evolve and interact in interstellar and circumstellar environments.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Modern work combines laboratory experiments, quantum chemical modelling and astronomical observations to understand the chemical pathways that operate under the extreme physical conditions of space.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] A major area of research concerns the formation of molecules on the surfaces of interstellar dust grains.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Low temperatures in dense clouds allow atoms and simple radicals to accrete onto grains, where reactions proceed through mechanisms such as quantum tunnelling.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] These processes influence the inventory of molecules present in the molecular cloud from which the Solar System formed, contributing to the carbon-rich chemistry of comets, asteroids, meteorites and interstellar dust particles.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] In dense clouds, thin ice mantles form on dust grains.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] The chemistry of these ices depends strongly on the form of hydrogen present: atomic hydrogen tends to produce reduced species such as H2O, CH4 and NH3, while molecular hydrogen allows heavier atoms to form species such as CO, CO2 and CN.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Ultraviolet radiation and cosmic rays drive further processing, producing increasingly complex organics.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Laboratory photochemistry experiments on simple ice analogues have produced amino acids, supporting the idea that prebiotic molecules may form in interstellar ices.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] The low densities of interstellar and interplanetary space allow unusual gas-phase chemistry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Many reactions that are symmetry-forbidden under terrestrial conditions can occur over long timescales, enabling the formation of molecules and ions that are unstable on Earth.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] A notable example is the H3+ ion, which plays a central role in interstellar ion–molecule chemistry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Astrochemistry overlaps with astrophysics and nuclear physics in the study of molecules formed in stellar environments.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Nuclear reactions in stellar interiors produce new elements, which can be transported to the surface by dredge-up events in stars with convective envelopes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] If such stars undergo significant mass loss, their winds may contain molecules whose rotational and vibrational transitions are observable with radio and infrared telescopes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Carbon-rich stars provide a striking example: as helium burning brings carbon to the surface, the molecular composition of the stellar wind changes dramatically, producing species such as silicates and water ice in their outer envelopes.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] A major focus of modern astrochemistry is the detection and formation of complex organic molecules.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Observations have shown that cosmic dust contains amorphous organic solids with mixed aromatic–aliphatic structures, and that polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) are widespread throughout the universe.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] PAHs may account for more than 20% of cosmic carbon and have been proposed as potential precursors to amino acids and nucleotides.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Several notable detections have highlighted the astrochemical relevance of complex organics.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] In 2012, astronomers reported the detection of the simple sugar glycolaldehyde around the protostellar binary IRAS 16293–2422, suggesting that biologically relevant molecules may form before planets themselves.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] In 2015, the *Philae* lander detected sixteen organic compounds on comet 67P, including acetamide, acetone, methyl isocyanate and propionaldehyde.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] In 2023, hydrogen cyanide and other organic molecules were detected in the plumes of Enceladus, a moon of Saturn, suggesting that chemically rich environments capable of supporting complex organic synthesis may exist in subsurface oceans.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Modern facilities such as the Atacama Large Millimeter/Submillimeter Array (ALMA) have enabled high-resolution mapping of molecular distributions in comets and other objects.
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] In 2014, ALMA observations revealed the spatial distribution of HCN, HNC, H2CO and dust in the comae of comets C/2012 F6 (Lemmon) and C/2012 S1 (ISON).
[src:microscale-chemistry/astrochemistry] Astrochemical modelling has also advanced.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] There are two main strands of the modern approach.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] Pioneering development in this area was carried out by Egerton C.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] El-Marsafy (1989) in Egypt, Stephen Thompson in the US and others.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] A further application of these ideas was the devising by Bradley of the Radmaste kits in South Africa, designed to make effective chemical experiments possible in developing countries in schools that lack the technical services (electricity, running water) taken for granted in many places.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] The other strand is the introduction of this approach into synthetic work, mainly in organic chemistry.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] Here the crucial breakthrough was achieved by Mayo, Pike and Butcher and by Williamson who demonstrated that inexperienced students were able to carry out organic syntheses on a few tens of milligrams, a skill previously thought to require years of training and experience.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] These approaches were accompanied by the introduction of some specialised equipment, which was subsequently simplified by Breuer without great loss of versatility.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] Scaling down experiments, when combined with modern projection technology, opened up the possibility of carrying out lecture demonstrations of the most hazardous kind in total safety.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] The approach has been adopted worldwide.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] It has become a major presence on the educational scene in the US, it is used to a lesser extent in the UK and it is used in many countries in institutions with staff who are enthusiastic about it.
[src:microscale-chemistry/microscale-chemistry] For example, in India, small scale chemistry/ microscale chemistry is now implemented in a few universities and colleges.
